In all of this I learned a very important lesson about faith. 

When standing on faith, things may not align how you expect them to and the path may not be linear. Things might not even make sense. Through it all, you got to trust the process.
I accepted the job right before Christmas and started this week and I’m very happy with it. Every step in this journey has brought me here and I’m excited to write this chapter of my story.

Still believing that God had something else in store. A couple of months ago, I was approached by a recruiter that I worked with in the past because she had a role that I “might” be a good fit for. Bruh. The role checked every box and some. It was exactly what I’d prayed for…

Still believing that God had something else in store. A couple of months ago, I was approached by a recruiter that I worked with in the past because she had a role that I “might” be a good fit for. Bruh. The role checked every box and some. It was exactly what I’d prayed for…

Right after that I was approached by my former company to come back for a role similar to what I’d prayed for. I took it to my wife and we prayed over it. On the surface it sounded good but it wasn’t it. They essentially offered me the job on the spot and I turned it down…

I told God that I’m still standing on the same faith that brought me here and that I trust Him to provide as He always has. I also prayed for discernment to decided what was for me because I knew that desperation breeds disobedience…

I felt trapped and stuck in this career. Even in the midst of it those feelings, I never questioned myself for making the decision to leave my old company. Eventually, after beating myself up for a while, I told God exactly what I wanted to  do and what I wanted the role to be…

From there, I bounced around to different roles/projects. I performed well but i knew that it wasn’t the type of job or lifestyle that I wanted to be a part of anymore. I struggled, though, because nothing that I wanted to do seemed to come in…

Before it was time for us to move I found a job as a consultant for a big 4 firm. At the time it was a huge win but I had no idea what I was really getting into. I had been in project management and erp implementation but consulting was an entirely different ball game..

Do I ask Jess to not do her residency? Do I be dishonest and “not move”? Do I leave this job and this company that I’d been with for 6 years? I chose the latter and I’ve never second-guessed that decision. I knew that as a husband I had to do whatever I could to support my wife…

A week go by and we still don’t talk about it so finally I reach back out and I’m told that moving to Atlanta would mean that I would have to resign from my role due to a “new company policy”. At that point I’m 1 month into marriage and I’m faced with a dilemma…

Until a few weeks. I was then told to go and enjoy getting married and me moving wouldn’t be a problem and have no impact on my job. We get back and a week or so later we find out that Jess got the Atlanta residency to which I tell my supervisor. No response happens…

Story time:

Around 3 years ago when Jess and I were about to get married, we knew there was a possibility of us moving to GA for her residency. I told my supervisor before leaving for the wedding and the honeymoon that I would possibly be moving to Atlanta but we won’t know…

My grandad always made it a point to teach anybody and everybody the game of golf, never wanting money for it, only wanting to grow the game. This is why this game is so important to me. This is why I aim so hard to continue his legacy. I want to continue to grow the game of golf

As he got older he would compete all over the southeast in various golf tournaments. Accomplishing 4 hole-in-ones. In the 60s he was hired by the city of Birmingham after the civil rights act. Often, times he’d be asked to rep the city in the tournaments.

He and his friends would make clubs out of sticks and poles and would sneak after hours to play on the course. This was usually met unkindly by the police. This never stopped him from pursuing and loving the game.

My grandad grew up in Brighton, AL during a time where black men and women were scarce in the sport. Where he lived, the local course would allow for him to work the grounds and caddy for the members but he was not able to play due to the color of his skin.

Random thread talking about my marriage and me as a husband. https://t.co/AQ9995xhsu
As her husband I want to facilitate the environment so that she can be her best self. I love who she is and I want for her to be able to explore every drop of her potential and ambition.
For the record, I do buy her things and do things for her. The point is that I don’t let those be the only ways through which I love her.

I could buy her whatever or do whatever for her and she’d appreciate it but most days she just wants me to be present when I’m with her, listen to her tell about her day and I tell her that I love her and I’m proud of her.
I aim to be in tune with her love languages so that I am loving her in the way that she best receives love. These are quality time and word of affirmation.

I aim to serve my wife daily. I seek ways that I can do specific things for her. For example, me cooking dinner is cool but I’ll try to make something that she will specifically love. Typically it’s a bacon cheeseburger with extra bbq sauce and French fries.

Here is where I shift to talking about being a husband. 

As a husband, I am constantly covering our family with prayer. I’m praying over my wife, our home, our cars, our careers, our everything. I aim to stay as connected to God as I possibly can.
She does handle all of the decorating and I stay out of the way of it. I handle fixing things and yard work and car stuff and she has no interest in doing any of that.

We don’t trip on societal gender roles. I do most of the cooking and cleaning because I love to cook and I work from home. It just makes sense. We make every financial decision together but she organizes the actual bill pays after our discussions.
We did premarital counseling and I would highly recommend it for everyone engaged or seriously dating. We also prioritize being in marriage counseling small groups as well. We love it.

I love our intentionality for growth. We aren’t perfect nor is our relationship perfect but we are fully committed to each other and we’re dedicated to building our marriage. We don’t just want a marriage that works we want a great marriage.

I also love our shared belief system of marriage. Being equally yoked with your s/o is fundamentally important. That’s spiritually, physically, financially, all of it. Not saying you have to be identical but you gotta be moving in the same direction.
One of my favorite aspects of Jess and I marriage is that we prioritize togetherness. Life gets busy at times but we are going to make sure we get our time together.
